## Next Up — Two Docker Improvements

These are infrastructure improvements that make the codebase cleaner and development faster.
Neither requires backend feature work. Both are Docker/config changes only.

---

### Item 1 — Docker Compose Watch

**What it is:**

Right now, every time you or your partner changes a Python file in the backend, you have to run
`docker compose up --build` to see the change take effect inside Docker. That rebuilds the entire
image — reinstalls all packages, copies all files — even if you just changed one line of code.
That can take 30–60 seconds every single time.

Docker Compose Watch fixes this. It watches your `./backend` folder on your Mac and the moment
you save a file, it syncs that change directly into the running container. No rebuild. No restart
of the whole image. The server picks it up in about 1–2 seconds.

The only time it still does a full rebuild is if you change `requirements.txt` (adding a new
Python package). That's correct — new packages have to be installed properly.

**How it works technically:**

Docker keeps a background process that monitors your files. When it sees a change, it copies just
that file into the running container. It's like a live sync between your Mac and the container.

**What we have to do:**

Two things:

1. Add a small config block to `docker-compose.yml` under the backend service
2. Add `--reload` to the uvicorn command so the server inside the container restarts when it sees a file change

Then instead of `docker compose up`, you run `docker compose watch`.

**It is NOT something in the Docker Desktop app** — it's purely a config change in the compose file
and a different command to run. Takes about 10 minutes to set up.

- [x] Add `develop: watch:` block to `docker-compose.yml`
- [x] Add `--reload` flag to backend uvicorn command
- [x] Run `docker compose watch` — Watch enabled
- [x] **Verify:** Change a Python file, save — backend synced without full rebuild ✓

